findings.detail:
When `flush()` is called on a freshly-constructed `ZStandardDecoder` that has never received any data (e.g. a 204 No Content response or an empty body), `self.decompressor.eof` will be `False` because no input was ever fed to it. This causes the code to raise `DecodingError("Zstandard data is incomplete")` even though an empty body is perfectly valid.

The BrotliDecoder avoids this by guarding `flush()` with `if not self.seen_data: return b""`. The same pattern should be applied here:

```python
def flush(self) -> bytes:
    ret = self.decompressor.flush()  # note: this is a no-op
    if not self.decompressor.eof:
        raise DecodingError("Zstandard data is incomplete")
    return bytes(ret)
```

Needs a `self.seen_data` flag (set in `decode()`) and an early return in `flush()` when no data was seen.
